               <p>1961. <persName id="def1-1961-18470816" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1961-18470816" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1961-18470816" type="age" value="28"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1961-18470816" type="surname" value="KEATES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1961-18470816" type="given" value="ELIJAH"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">ELIJAH KEATES</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18470816-1961-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18470816-1961-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18470816-1961-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp> for stealing 12 ounces of sugar, value 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; the goods of the <persName id="t18470816-name-1252" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1252" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18470816-1961-offence-1 t18470816-name-1252"></join>London Dock Company</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470816-name-1253" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1253" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1253" type="surname" value="EGERTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1253" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>SAMUEL EGERTON</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman H</hi> 193.) On the 1st of Aug. I was on duty in the London Docks—the prisoner was on duty as a constable there—he had been doing duty on the East-quay the night before—he came to the station—I followed him, and saw him go to his cupboard, unlock it, put his hand in, pull something out, put it into his hat, and put his hat on a shelf over the dresser in the kitchen—he then said he would go and buy something for his breakfast—he put on his hat and was going out—we met the inspector in the passage, I told him—he ordered the prisoner to pull his hat off, and in it was this sugar—the inspector asked him where he got it—he said he picked it up the other night as he was coming off duty on the North-quay.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PARNELL.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What time was this? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Between seven and eight o'clock on Sunday morning—I was about a yard and a half behind him—I should say the cupboard is about a yard wide—he opened the door quite wide—I saw that plainly—there are six samples of sugar—he was in the same division as I am, and was engaged at the same place—his pay as a policeman as 18<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 7 1/2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. a week—he had been seven or eight months em<lb></lb>ployed in the docks.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470816-name-1254" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1254" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1254" type="surname" value="MADDOX"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1254" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE MADDOX.</persName>
                  </hi> I am an inspector of police. I saw the prisoner's hat taken off, these samples were in it; he said he did not know what it was—I found it was sugar—he said he picked it up in the docks—it was his duty to take care of the property in the docks, and to report anything he found to me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> How are these things got at? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> These samples are nailed on the outside of each cask, with a nail through them, and are samples of what the sugar is in the cask—if he picked any of these up, it was his duty to bring them to me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470816-name-1255" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1255" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1255" type="surname" value="RUDKINS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1255" type="given" value="DANIEL"></interp>DANIEL RUDKINS.</persName>
                  </hi> I am an officer of the Dock-Company. I know some sugars were landed partly damp, and a sample was drawn and nailed on the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184708160224"></xptr>
               <p>cask till the sampling was completed—these would remain on the top till the lotting was completed.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character.)</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18470816-1961-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
